{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627768"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17149"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17149"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.35,0.05,0.51,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76895"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9839"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23046"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76895"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDopamine is an endogenous catecholamine that has dose-dependent effects on the cardiovascular system through multiple receptor types.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cardiovascular effects of dopamine at high doses?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasoconstriction","Increased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasodilation","No effect on cardiac contractility with peripheral vasodilation","Increased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasoconstriction","Decreased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasodilation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt high doses, dopamine causes \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs through activation of beta-1 adrenergic receptors in the heart (increasing contractility and heart rate) and alpha-1 adrenergic receptors in blood vessels (causing vasoconstriction).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of dopamine\u0027s effects at high doses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E - While contractility is increased, high-dose dopamine causes vasoconstriction, not vasodilation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased cardiac contractility and peripheral vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E - Dopamine increases rather than decreases cardiac contractility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo effect on cardiac contractility with peripheral vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E - Dopamine has significant effects on contractility and causes vasoconstriction at high doses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt lower doses, dopamine primarily activates dopamine-1 receptors, causing selective vasodilation in renal and mesenteric vessels. The cardiac and peripheral vascular effects become more prominent as the dose increases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dopamine increases cardiac contractility and heart rate by binding to beta-1 adrenergic receptors.","Dopamine causes vasoconstriction at high doses through alpha-1 adrenergic receptor activation.","At low doses, dopamine causes renal and mesenteric vasodilation through dopamine-1 receptor activation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17149"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T18:30:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T18:31:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9839"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76895"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re